    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-10-16T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-10-16T16:00:00-05:00" n="761"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d761">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 652.119/1886</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_WJE1"
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Willard</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-10-16T17:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 16, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1681. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_CTL1">Chadbourne</persName>
                    [from War Trade Board]:<note n="1" xml:id="d761fn1">See last paragraph for
                        advice of repetition to <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MG1"
                            >McFadden</persName>, War Trade Board representative at Paris.</note>
                </p>
                <p>No. 313. Referring Embassy’s 1886, October 3, 7 p.m., your 303,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d761fn2">Not printed.</note> and Department’s 1610, September 27, 5
                    p.m., our 282,<note n="2" xml:id="d761fn3">Not printed.</note> and previous
                        cables<note n="2" xml:id="d761fn4">Not printed.</note> concerning the
                    purchase of mules by A[merican] E[xpeditionary] F[orces]. The War Department has
                    agreed to make available out of its stocks, 20,000 tons of sulphate of ammonia
                    for the purpose of securing release of 50,000 mules. You are authorized to
                    assure the Spanish authorities that the United States will permit the
                    exportation to Spain of 20,000 tons of sulphate of ammonia at the rate of 3,000
                    tons a month beginning in October, if the Spanish Government will permit the
                    immediate release for the A.E.F. of 50,000 mules.</p>
                <p>If this arrangement is made, it is our intention that the licenses for the
                    sulphate of ammonia shall be allocated in accordance with a plan approved by our
                    representative in Spain.</p>
                <p>We are repeating this cablegram to Paris in our No. 385 to <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MG1">McFadden</persName>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
